{{Infobox officeholder | name = Francis Victor DuPont | image = Francis_Victor_DuPont.png | caption = | nationality = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | office = Administrator of the [[Federal Highway Administration]] | term_start = 1953 | term_end = 1955 | predecessor = [[Thomas Harris MacDonald]] | successor = [[Charles Dwight Curtiss]] }}
'''Francis V. du Pont''' was a member of the famous [[Du Pont Family]] of [[DuPont|DuPont Chemical]], based in [[Wilmington, Delaware]], and an official connected with the development of public roads and highways in the United States.<ref name="DoT">{{cite web|url=https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/administrators/fdupont.cfm|title=Administrators|publisher=US Federal Highway Administration|accessdate=13 May 2017}} {{PD-notice}}</ref>
The son of T. Coleman du Pont, who was the president of DuPont Chemical, Francis Victor du Pont was a member of the Delaware State Highway Commission from 1922 to 1949. He also served as chairman of the commission.<ref name="DoT"/> In this role, Du Pont played a major role in the development of the financing, engineering, and initial construction of the [[Delaware Memorial Bridge]], the fifth longest suspension span in the world, which was opened to traffic on July 1, 1951.<ref name="DoT"/> In 1953, he was appointed Commissioner of the [[Bureau of Public Roads|US Bureau of Public Roads]]. While serving as Commissioner, he recommended a highway program that led to legislation under which the [[Interstate Highway System]] was constructed.<ref name="DoT"/> He resigned his Federal post on January 1, 1956.<ref name="DoT"/>
